TY  - JOUR
T1  - When Does Decision Autonomy Increase Expatriate Managers' Adjustment? An Empirical Test
AU  - Takeuchi, Riki
AU  - Shay, Jeffrey P.
AU  - Jiatao, Li
Y1  - 2008/02/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.30696751
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2008.30696751
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 45
EP  - 60
VL  - 51
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - To enhance understanding of expatriate adjustment, we examine the effect of the decision autonomy afforded to expatriate managers on their own adjustment as well as the moderating effect of global integration pressure. We further investigate the mitigating effect of a parent company's operational experience with a particular foreign subsidiary on this relationship. We examine these issues using survey data from 187 expatriate general managers and 24 corporate headquarter executives working in the global hotel industry. The results of the study support the hypotheses postulated. We discuss implications of these findings.
AB  - To enhance understanding of expatriate adjustment, we examine the effect of the decision autonomy afforded to expatriate managers on their own adjustment as well as the moderating effect of global integration pressure. We further investigate the mitigating effect of a parent company's operational experience with a particular foreign subsidiary on this relationship. We examine these issues using survey data from 187 expatriate general managers and 24 corporate headquarter executives working in the global hotel industry. The results of the study support the hypotheses postulated. We discuss implications of these findings.
